issue_body:
Windows 7/MingW x64 GCC 5.3
With dnn_mnist_ex.cpp sample, I found that restarting training process does not work correctly - only first saving of state file can be loaded. After first sate file is saved, training process fails to overwrite it with renaming temporary file

While debugging, I found at file https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/master/dlib/dnn/trainer.h, line s 705-707:
```c++
    // Now that we know the state is safely saved to disk, delete the old sync
    // file and move the .tmp file to it.
    std::rename(tempfile.c_str(), sync_filename.c_str());
```

The result code of std::rename is not checked. And on Windows it returns -1:
```c++
     int res = std::rename(tempfile.c_str(), sync_filename.c_str());
     if (res)
           perror("Error renaming file");
```

The output is: *Error renaming file: File exists*

This is Windows-specific issue, according to http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/cstdio/rename
>If newname names an existing file, the function may either fail or override the existing file, depending on the specific system and library implementation.


If I remove state file manually wile training process is running - it is saved, but only once until I remove it again

like this
for(int i=0;i<detectors.size()-1;i++)
{
for (auto&& d : detectorsi)
{
dlib::rect_detection rect;
rect.detection_confidence=d.detection_confidence;
rect.rect=d.rect;
std::string::size_type sz; // alias of size_t
rect.weight_index=std::stoi (d.label,&sz);
rects.push_back(rect);
}
}

Just a heads up, but this is what `Presence`'s proto should look like:

```
message Presence {
  optional bool reachable = 1;
  optional bool available = 2;
  optional DeviceStatus device_status = 6;
  optional MoodSetting mood_setting = 9;
  optional LastSeen last_seen = 10;
}
```

Note that `MoodMessage` has been changed to `MoodSetting` -- this is the correct result when using `QueryPresenceRequest`.

When I try to use TinyDB on an existing JSON like this one :
`{
    "_default": [
        value1,
        value2,
        ...
    ]
}`

It does not work but when I try on an empty json, TinyDB generates a json looking like this : 
`{
    "_default": {
        "1": value1,
        "2": value2,
        ...
    }
}`

Why use an object with indexes and not a simple array ? Is it possible to configure TinyDB to use an array ?

I'm using the (hugely useful) `Execute Time` nbextension, which produces cell metadata like this:

    {
     "cell_type": "code",
     "execution_count": null,
     "metadata": {
      "ExecuteTime": {
       "end_time": "2016-08-15T11:49:40.736068",
       "start_time": "2016-08-15T11:49:40.145965"
      },
      "code_folding": [],
      "collapsed": false
     },
     "outputs": [],
     "source": []
    }

But naturally I end up with a load of changes seen by git after running `nbstripout` because of re-running the cells and updating the `ExecuteTime` field. Would you accept a pull request explicitly stripping this out, or alternatively one which strips all but whitelisted metadata entries?

